This is based on the plot Z= - (X^2) - (Y^2) (known as a paraboloid) but instead of being a continuous surface, I've discretized it so that it is formed from a collection of varying height square prisms. Three STL files included:
Paraboloid.stl is for a machine with a single extruder. it is formed from 16x16 square prisms, where each square is 3mm per side. ParaboloidOddSquares.stl and ParaboloidEvenSquares.stl are used for a dual extruder machine so that every other square is a different color (same dimensions as above) Finally I've include the openSCAD source which allows you to parametrize the number of squares per side as well as the size of each square.

Last year I got one drawer full with two people picking for a similar amount of time, so roughly double the yield with the tool... small green berries are easily weeded out by dumping the batch into water and the green ones float....now to solve the issue of weeding out the leaves... that is the major labor sticking point, anyway just finished all of this years berries and they have been frozen so I can have a healthy snack year round.

I use .1in copper wire to connect the parts and a stiff aluminum rod in the bottom corner, I believe copper wire would work in all three through holes just find though.  
most parts are universal with the exception of the handle sides

comments.text: Good luck on your new kit! For Solidworks, I would suggest using either a swept cut or doing a larger box deeper in and using the fillet tool on the edges to smooth it out, just be aware that supports could be tricky in the current orientation, so you might want to change the printing orientation to avoid using supports. Maybe you can try with the stand upside down as long as you can keep it adhered to the plate?  For tips on printing with wood, I would suggest using bigger extruder nozzles if possible like a .5 instead of .4 or .45.  Also, clean out the nozzle with another kind of filament when you finish printing if you can.  I personally had problems with my Prusa i3 (mine was technically a cheaper chinese knockoff but it does work with good filament).  Wood filament has the wood fibers in it that can get stuck and jam, especially if it is cheap filament.

description.text: A simple series of circles or squares for calibrating your DropLit build size parameters in Creation Workshop.  Circle diameters are 20mm, 40mm and 60mm. NOT FOR PRINTING, SEE INSTRUCTIONS.

• Load and slice this STL in Creation Workshop
  • Go into 'Slice View'; verify Slice 1 is displayed
  • Active the projection of Slice 1 from the button in the lower left
  • Carefully measure the diameter/width of one of the features. Write down the measurement
  • Deactivate the projection of Slice 1
  • Click 'Configure'
  • Click 'Configure Machine'
  • Click 'Adjust' under 'Build Size'
  • Input the file specified diameter/width of the feature you measured in the left X- and Y-size boxes. Stock diameters/widths are: 20mm, 40mm and 60mm
  • Input your obtained measurement in the right X- and Y-size boxes.
  • Click 'OK'
    • This will resize your printable area and scale your prints accurately. Thusly, a 100mm part prints at 100mm

description.text:
Introduction
=================
WARNING: Prototype!

In an attempt to upgrade my Mendel to a MendelMax alike X axis (where the X belt is 90 degrees rotated like the Pruse belt path) I redesigned the X-ends to hold a 22mm trapezoid or ACME nut.
Aditionally, I added a tensioner system in order to be able to modify belt tension on the X axis without abusing the carriage attachment for that. The goal is to use the original Mendel length of smooth rod. As such the block is a fair bit longer than some of the MendelMax designs I have seen; this allows the tensioner system to be placed on it as well. Details
=======
  • Modelled in SolidWorks 2012
  • Uses 2 LM8UU bearings
  • Bearings are clamped down with 2x 3mm screws
  • Rods are clamped down with 2x 4mm screws
  • Uses 4x 608 bearings for the belt path
    • Why not in OpenSCAD? Because prototyping and fitting things together is a breeze in SW - as soon as I work out the issues with this design I will put up a link to the design with an OpenSCAD version as well. There are 2 versions of this design, one with nice curves and one with a square base block. The rounded version turned out to be impossible to print in one piece using ABS; splitting it into two halves did not help much.
    The normal version is using a square base and has much material removed in an attempt to reduce warping and decrease print times. Both designs most likely require a heated chamber and/or the use of PLA to print properly; as I only have ABS at the moment and only a heated bed I can not get this to print straight.
Words of Wisdom

I have posted this for inspiration and as a base for another iteration of this design. It should fit a Mendel (standard rod length) and MendelMax (assuming your rods are long enough). The distance between the centers of the smooth rod and trapezoid spindle is 29mm, NOT 30mm like on the... errr... prusa? Instructions

• Use a heated chamber with ABS or PLA if you have non-warping plastic.
  • Print the rounded version without support
  • Print the normal version with support as the clamping section is sticking out in thin air
  • Print a tensioner bracket and push block
  • Put a 40mm bolt through the tensioner block from the back, through the tensioner, add the push block, a washer and a nut
  • Optionally: use a longer bolt, add a spring to generate an even tension (use a strong spring or you will induce back-lash!)
  • Optionally: print a second tensioner bracket and insert it into the second holder on the other side of the body. Use a longer 8mm bolt or threaded rod to extend from the primary tensioner to the secondary tensioner. This should allow for more force on the tensioner before it breaks.

title: Netatmo Rainsensor Support for Hand Rails

description.text:
I like my Netatmo, it tells me how the weather is at home when I am abroad. Want to see what the temperature was at a certain day in the past? Take a look at your Netatmo smartphone app and you will know.  
There is just one thing I disliked: The rainsensor was attached with some cable fixer to the hand rail of my house.  
So I designed the Netatmo Rainsensor Holder to properly attach it to the hand rail. I enclose the Sketchup-file, so you can easily adapt to the dimensions of your own handrail.  
I printed in 3 pieces to avoid printing excessive support. I used some super-glue to attach part 2 on part 3. Print parts stable enough so they don't crack when you tighten the screws.  
Have fun!  
P.S. Sketchup gave me a hard time to properly draw the 4th hole for the screws. After trying for the 100's time, I gave up. You might are better than I am with Sketchup and can get it fixed...
